segments.text: What is the current impact and what will be the future impact of the black women in athletics?
The current impact?
They're good.
They're strong.
They're real good.
I can't understand.
I wish I knew more about physiology because
It's funny that in the United States, I'm talking about track now, the black women are better sprinters, better jumpers, better runners, of course, because they're stronger.
Distance events, they're lacking in that area.
But you can look at my team picture in a minute, and there weren't very many white girls on the team.

They seem to just kind of, they've taken over all the events, and I don't really know why, because you go to, you see the German teams, the Russian teams, who are beating our teams, that are all black, their teams are all white.
Now, I know drugs enter a little bit there, but I'm not so naive to think that our women are probably not on drugs, too.
Probably not as heavily as they are.
And not all the girls.
But I don't understand that.
I think the black women athletes are going to be an incentive to the younger black women.
I've coached over the years on the junior high and high school level, and I always tried to pick out, like, Evelyn Ashford is our best American sprinter.
I would put her poster in the locker room and talk about her and Wilma Rudolph, and I think that inspires those kids, those young people.
With the increased money being spent on women's athletics, do you feel the recruitment of women athletes will become more intense in the future?
I think it will.
I don't think it will ever be.
Well, it may be.
But it will be a while before it's as bad as men's recruiting problems that we have.
it's tough, especially when that money comes in, because those girls will go anywhere.
You know, it was really easy when there was one school with a little bit of money, or everybody was pretty equal.
The problem is, you've got major colleges with a lot of money, and some of the colleges
that have stronger women's programs than what the major college does, they don't have so much money.
And that's a real problem for them.
So it's not real equal.
So it's gonna come down to, it's not right now,
But I think it probably will end up who's going to give the most money.
I hear a lot of girls now, it's funny to hear them say, well, maybe I'll get a car, maybe I'll get this, maybe I'll get some extra money here.
They've seen the men get it, and they think they're going to get it now.
I didn't hear that when I was in school.
Thought never crossed your mind.
But now, if you're really good, you can hold out for a better deal.
And women are getting to that point.
I hope it didn't happen, but I think it probably will.
What was your reaction of being the first woman inducted into the Texas A&M Hall of Fame?
Do you feel there should be such an institution, Texas A&M?
Yeah, I think it's good to have...
the Hall of Fame, I think it's going to have the Worker's Student Association, and everybody kind of has their own area.
I was in shock when I got it.
As a matter of fact, I'm on the board of directors of the Letterman's Association, and I know they do that every year, but I never expected it for myself.
And it was almost like I thought, well, maybe I'm not worthy of it to be put up there with those demands.
I still feel that way.
A lot of people told me I'm stupid for thinking that because in their eyes and for what I do, it's just as good as what Curtis Dickman would do.
But it really surprised me and I wasn't expecting it at all.
I'm proud that I was chosen for it.
I'm real proud that I was the first because I was also the first on the scholarship at A&M for a male-led program.
I was the first female on a full athletic scholarship at A&M.
So it kind of went step and step with that.
But my harsh reaction when the guy called me was, are you sure you have the right person?
And he kept saying, well, I think so.
Didn't you first say?
No.
Jackie Sherrill has made major changes concerning women's athletics.
This firing of Kay Dawn came under scrutiny.
Do you feel women's athletics at A&M will grow under Jackie Sherrill?
Well, see that, first of all, Kay Dawn and I were very...
And I loved her a lot.
She supported me.
In 1980, she went around to all the Aggie clubs and got them to donate money so that I could travel.
I ran under Texas A&M Track Club.
And my money for my travel was all given to these former Aggies.
She did a lot for me.
I think she did a lot for Amy while she was here.
My gosh, before she came, we didn't have any money.
And I knew when that happened
I don't really know the nitty-gritty of it all, but I know it was really bad.
I like Lynn Hickey.
I think she's going to do a good job.
Sometimes I wonder how coaches like Jackie Sherrill, who are athletic directors,
also coach and keep their mind equal for all sports.
It might be a better deal if you had someone like K-9 who wasn't the basketball coach or the track coach.
Then again on the other side of the coin, if you're a coach you know what you need, the wants and needs of your athletes and hopefully you can see that in other sports too.
I think you can't help but have the women's programs at A&M improve.
I don't think they were that bad.
I think they were really growing for a while, and they kind of were in a slump, and I think that might be what happened there.
I'm not real sure what Jackie Sherrill's done.
I mean, I got a letter from him, which I thought would be nice.
Mm-hmm.
And I'm sure it will grow.
I think if he's the kind of man that I think he is, he's going to want A&M.
He's looking at it for A&M, not...
You're going to have to put your things in perspective.
You want A&M to have good programs, not just the men to have good programs, but A&M as a whole.
And athletics should be men's athletics and women's should be athletics and A&M.
And we have both sexes, you know, but playboy opposites.
So I think it's going to grow, and I think it will grow with him because I think he's smart.
He's a smart person, and I think he knows what he needs.
And I think John David Crowe does, too.
And it was real funny.
Everybody kept apologizing to me at the press conference they called after I had received the award.
I was really kind of shocked that they were apologizing to me because they felt like they hadn't done enough for me for the accomplishments that I had gotten.
Which, you know, I never really felt that way.
And then after I kept apologizing to them, then I started thinking, well,
You know, if I had been a man, if I had made a team, maybe I wouldn't have come.
Of course, I wasn't a world record holder like Randy Mattson.
You know, I think he's, gosh.
See, I still think of myself as not near as good as a man.
I just, it really, I don't, you know, and I don't think I can go in there expecting the same things that Randy Mattson does.
It was real funny that they kept apologizing to me.
I kept wondering why they were apologizing to me.
They just kept saying, we hadn't done enough for you.
I just can't believe you did this.
We've never recognized you.
We've done enough.
Which kind of makes you, then you go, well, yeah, maybe you had to recognize me enough, but I never had felt that way.
I think I was dealt a good love, and especially since they supported me after I had graduated.
They had given me all the money, and it took a lot of money to send me, because all the meets that I competed in were pretty much in the West Coast.
So every pentathlon meet I went to, it was like getting on a plane, it was like a major trip.
So I've
What do you feel is the future of collegiate women's athletics?
Well, I think they're going to really grow.
I think they're going to start getting some publicity on television.
We're seeing more of that, more of the nationals being televised.
and they don't keep brains on it, like they're not meant to.
Because, well, this year in particular, it'll come to, you know, all the crew and props that they had, and it could happen with tremendous progress.
With the growth rate that we're going to see, we're going to be very careful and watch what we're posting.
And publicity-wise, that will increase, which may also help the professional programs that we're talking about.
It's like you can't start anything in college until you get your high school programs going.
You can't do anything professional until you've got your college programs working.
So the 101 would be the end of it.
This is the last question.
Do you feel that women's athletics will ever be the same as men's athletics as far as funding?
No.
No, no.
That's what we get for Eve getting Adam to athlete.
No, I don't.
I think...
I just don't think it ever will be.
Maybe 50 years from now it might be, but in the very...
near to 30 years from now type future, I don't think that it would be.
I don't know why.
I think maybe one reason why is the men's program's football is the biggest moneymaker.
And they're going to get the most publicity on television, professional, and NCAA.
And even in high school, they do.
So men are going to always be caught because of football.
And that's always going to be the biggest sport.
Then you're going to .
I don't think they'll ever be equal.
We'll be running close, but I don't think they'll ever be equal.
And we may be equal in certain sports.
But the bigger sports, basketball, women's basketball will never be equal to men's basketball.
Track, they're pretty equal.
I'm going to have to admit they are.
Right now, they're under one coach.
Smaller sports tend to be that way.
Swimming, pretty equal.
You see the Olympic swimming, the NCAA swimming, it's usually the same way.
High schools now, in track, they're going, state meets are the same.
They used to be separate.
The girls' state was this weekend, the boys' was this weekend, now they're the same weekend.
So you can see some improvements there, and it'll probably come around now.
Nationals will probably end up being the same weekend, too.
The end of the nationals, NCAA, in track, will probably be the same weekend.
That's it.
That's it.
